@node Introduction "AquaQuick v1.0 Documentation"

Introduction
~~~~~~~~~~~~
When a BBS user logs on, a various number of bulletins are displayed
before him. The dilemma for you (the sysop) is that some people want to
see everything (WeekTop, TopUploaders, LastCallers etc) but some don't
want anything of that. Well, AquaQuick is the solution! It lets you have
up to 9 login modes to offer your users. For example, you can make it ask
"(N)ormal, (S)hortened or (Q)uick Logon (N/s/q)?". Pressing N shows all
the screens, S gives a shorter logon (only WeekTop and LastCallers for
instance), and Q throws the user directly to mailscan.

What's wrong with the normal quick logons ('Y Q'/'N Q' at the ANSI
prompt)? you might ask yourself. Well, that only gives you 2 "modes", and
if you always want to show something or run some particular MCI commands
at every logon, AquaQuick is the solution! Then you should disable the
normal quick logons by putting DISABLE_QUICK_LOGONS in BBS:Node(x).info
(for /X 3.0+).

If the user always want to use a particular mode he can configure that
easily with the configuration door. Then he won't get any question from
the main door at logon.
@endnode

@node Requirements "AquaQuick v1.0 Documentation"

Requirements
~~~~~~~~~~~~
- An Amiga with OS 2.0 or higher.

- AmiExpress, SigmaExpress or any compatible program.
@endnode

@node Installation "AquaQuick v1.0 Documentation"

Installation
~~~~~~~~~~~~
Make a directory 'Doors:AquaQuick'. It should contain 'AquaQuick' (the
main door), 'AquaQuickConfig' (configuration door), 'AquaQuick.info'
(configuration icon) and 'AquaQuick.Prompt' (text specifying the
"prompt"). Then (for /X 3.0+) put the provided command icon 'quick.info'
in your SYSCmd drawer and 'quickcfg.info' in your BBSCmd drawer.

AquaQuick is perfectly safe to make resident. The changes you have to make
to the command icons in that case are: Change the value of "LOCATION" to
"AquaQuick" and add the tooltype "RESIDENT". The configuration door
AquaQuickConfig can also be made resident but there's not much to gain
with that - it's probably not run very often.


You must remove all bulletins that would normally be displayed at logon.
They are:

BBS:BULL[<acs>].<suffix>
BBS:Node<x>/BULL[<acs>].<suffix>


Leave 'BBS:Node<x>/Logon[<acs>].<suffix>'. That is where AquaQuick is
started from, using an MCI command:

---------Cut-here------------------
~
~CC_QUICK|
-----------Cut-here----------------

In case you didn't know: Any MCI text must start with a '~', and every MCI
command must end with a '|', a space (' ') or a newline!

If you have other doors that must always be run at logon, you can put them
there too. For example if you're using Announce (written by me), the text
should look something like this:

---------Cut-here------------------
~
~CC_ANNLOGON|~CC_QUICK|
-----------Cut-here----------------

Maybe unvalidated users shouldn't be able to use AquaQuick. Then make sure
to have several Logon[<acs>].txt files, for example Logon100.txt (for
normal users) and Logon.txt (for unvalidated users), the last one without
~CC_QUICK.


The file 'Doors:AquaQuick/AquaQuick.Prompt' is what is shown to the user
when he shall select login mode. You can write whatever you like there.


You should disable the normal quick logon way - 'Y Q'/'N Q' at the ANSI
prompt - at least if you have MCI commands which must be run at every
logon (for example Announce). For /X 3.0+, put the tooltype
'DISABLE_QUICK_LOGONS' in the BBS:Node(x).info icons.


Now you must @{"configure" Link Configuration} the door...
@endnode

@node Configuration "AquaQuick v1.0 Documentation"

Tooltypes in 'Doors:AquaQuick/AquaQuick.info':
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 @{" KEY.<num>        " Link ttKEY}
 @{" DESC.<num>       " Link ttDESC}
 @{" DISP.<num>.<num> " Link ttDISP}
 @{" DEFAULT          " Link ttDEFAULT}
 @{" CALLERSLOG       " Link ttCALLERSLOG}
@endnode

@node ttKEY "AquaQuick v1.0 Documentation"

Template: KEY.<num>=<string>                    At least one required! :)
Example : KEY.2=Yes

These tooltypes specify what choices the user can make. You can write
strings here but it is the *first character* that the user can type to
choose that alternative. But when the choice is made, the entire string
will be displayed. For example, let the KEY.x tooltypes in the icon be:

KEY.1=Normal
KEY.2=Quick

What the user can press at the prompt is N and Q. If he presses N then
"Normal" is written. If he types Q then "Quick" is written.
@endnode

@node ttDESC "AquaQuick v1.0 Documentation"

Template: DESC.<num>=<string>               Optional, default: "" (ugly!)
Example : DESC.2=Always quick logon

These strings will be shown in the configuration door as descriptions for
the logon modes.
@endnode

@node ttDISP "AquaQuick v1.0 Documentation"

Template: DISP.<num>.<num>=<path pattern>                       Optional.
Example : DISP.2.1=BBS:BullNotQuick%X.%S

These tooltypes specify what texts to display for the various login modes.
The first <num> says what @{"KEY.<num>" Link ttKEY} it belongs to. The second <num> is a
counter starting with 1. For example, if login mode number 2 is chosen,
the door first displays the textfile specified by DISP.2.1, then DISP.2.2,
then DISP.2.3, and so on until no more DISP.2.x tooltype can be found.

<Path pattern> can be just a plain path to a textfile, or it can contain
one or more of the following codes:

  "%N" - is replaced with the node number
  "%X" - is replaced with an access level
  "%S" - is replaced with a suffix ("TXT" for example)

An example.. Let's say the node number is 3 and the user has access level
100 and a screentype with the suffix "PCT". Then if a path pattern is
"BBS:Node%N/BullFull%X.%S" the door will search for text files in this
order and display the first one that it finds:

BBS:Node3/BullFull100.PCT
BBS:Node3/BullFull100.TXT
BBS:Node3/BullFull95.PCT
BBS:Node3/BullFull95.TXT
BBS:Node3/BullFull90.PCT
BBS:Node3/BullFull90.TXT
...
BBS:Node3/BullFull5.PCT
BBS:Node3/BullFull5.TXT
BBS:Node3/BullFull.PCT
BBS:Node3/BullFull.TXT
@endnode

@node ttDEFAULT "AquaQuick v1.0 Documentation"

Template: DEFAULT=<num>                                         Optional.
Example : DEFAULT=1

This determines which logon mode should be the default. That is if the
user presses Return, that mode will be used. If you don't want any mode to
be default, don't use this tooltype.
@endnode

@node ttCALLERSLOG "AquaQuick v1.0 Documentation"

Template: CALLERSLOG=<YES|NO>                       Optional. Default: NO
Example : CALLERSLOG=NO

If "CALLERSLOG=YES" then the door will write to the callerslog what choice
the user made.
@endnode

